            . I am servant to Henry Harris Fox; he lives in <placeName id="t18301028-46-crimeloc259">Hatton-garden</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18301028-46-crimeloc259" type="placeName" value="Hatton-garden"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18301028-46-crimeloc259" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301028-46-off257 t18301028-46-crimeloc259"></join> - when I came down on the 18th of October, two men were repairing the flue of the chimney; I saw the prisoner there afterwards - he staid some time, and went away between eight and nine o'clock; I missed a silver table spoon, which I had used and left on or near the sink.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301028-46-person494">
                  JAMES 
                  JACKSON
               <interp inst="t18301028-46-person494" type="surname" value="JACKSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301028-46-person494" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18301028-46-person494" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18301028-46-deflabel260" type="occupation">chimney-sweeper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18301028-46-defend490 t18301028-46-deflabel260"></join>; the prisoner was in my employ; I was at the prosecutor's house- I afterwards heard of the spoon being lost, and charged the prisoner with it; he denied it - I took Mr. Fox to my house, searched, and found it in the cellar, broken in two; there was another young man with me at the house, but he did not stay five minutes.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18301028-46-person495">
                  WILLIAM 
                  BROWN EDWARDS
               <interp inst="t18301028-46-person495" type="surname" value="BROWN EDWARDS"></interp>
